    en: "A landlord can enter a tenant's apartment without notice in a real emergency — a fire, a gas leak, a burst pipe flooding other units, or a situation where someone inside may be hurt. But a landlord who labels every visit an emergency to skip notice is violating the tenant's right to quiet enjoyment. The right of a tenant to privacy in the rental home is common law in New York, reinforced by the warranty of habitability (RPL 235-b). Repeated unauthorized entry can be trespass, harassment, and a constructive eviction."
